# ZenStack v3 Rules

ZenStack v3 uses its own Kysely-based ORM engine (no Prisma). The schema file `zenstack/schema.zmodel` is the single source of truth.

## Schema Rules

- ALL models defined in `zenstack/schema.zmodel` — never create raw Prisma `.prisma` files
- Every model MUST have explicit `@@allow` and `@@deny` policies — no model ships without access control
- Run `npx zenstack generate` after every `zenstack/schema.zmodel` change, then run migrations
- Do NOT install or import `@prisma/client` directly — use ZenStack's generated client from `lib/db.ts`
- Do NOT add a `generator client { provider = "prisma-client-js" }` block — v3 does not use Prisma Client codegen
- Two plugin blocks are required: `plugin typescript { provider = "@core/typescript" }` and `plugin policy { provider = "@zenstackhq/plugin-policy" }` — do NOT use `@core/enhancer` (v2 only)
- Generated files (`zenstack/schema.ts`, `zenstack/models.ts`, `zenstack/input.ts`) are auto-generated — never edit them manually

## Multi-Tenant Isolation

- Consultants NEVER see other consultants' data — enforce at the schema level with `@@allow` policies scoped to `auth().orgId`
- Magic Link sessions are scoped to a single project/supplier pair — enforce in schema with `@@allow` policies checking session context
- Never rely on application code for tenant isolation — the schema is the security boundary

## Enhanced Client

- Import the ZenStack enhanced client from `lib/db.ts`
- The enhanced client automatically applies access policies based on the current user context
- Always pass the auth context when creating the enhanced client
